<h1>How to</h1>
<ol>
  <li>find your <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">libgnome-shell.so</code> file. In my case, That is in <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">/usr/lib/gnome-shell/</code></li>
  <li>If you cannot find the file, you can use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">find</code>. Find the color code <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">#4f194c</code>.</li>
  <li>Eg. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">sudo find /usr/ -type f -print 2&gt; /dev/null | xargs grep -i "#4f194c" 2&gt;/dev/null</code></li>
  <li>And just modify the color code in about <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">39116</code>th row. In my case, I set the color code <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">#000000</code>(black).</li>
  <li>And DONE!! There will be no-purple-screen in your loging situation!</li>
</ol>

